'3:1': [
{sup:1, word:"Moses", lines:["Moses was the first fully qualified servant of God in the Bible, and God&rsquo;s calling of Moses is the standard of His calling of all His servants. As one who was called and sent by God to His people, Moses typifies Christ as the Apostle sent to us from God and with God ({Joh6:46|John 6:46}; {Joh8:16|8:16}, {Joh8:29|29}; {Heb3:1|Heb. 3:1}-{Heb3:6|6})."]},
{sup:"a", word:"mountain", vrefs:"Exo. 4:27; 18:5; 24:13; 1&nbsp;Kings 19:8; cf. Num. 10:33"},
],
'3:2': [
{sup:"a", word:"And", vrefs:"vv. 2-8: cf. Acts 7:30-35; Exo. 3:16; 4:5; Heb. 11:27"},
{sup:"1b", word:"Angel", vrefs:"Gen. 22:11-12; Judg. 6:11-24; Acts 7:35; cf. Exo. 14:19", lines:["The title the Angel of Jehovah refers mainly to Christ, the Son of God, as the One sent by God (cf. {Joh8:42|John 8:42}) to save His people from their situation of suffering (cf. {Jdg6:12|Judg. 6:12}-{Jdg6:22|22}; {Jdg13:3|13:3}-{Jdg13:22|22}). According to vv. {Exo3:2|2} and {Exo3:6|6}, the Angel of Jehovah, the sent One, was Jehovah Himself, the sending One (cf. {Zec2:6|Zech. 2:6}-{Zec2:11|11}), and Jehovah is the Triune God (vv. {Exo3:6|6}, {Exo3:15|15}). For the purpose of calling and sending Moses, God, the sending One, appeared to him as the sent One (cf. {Joh20:21|John 20:21}). See {Act7:30|Acts 7:30}-{Act7:31|31} and {Act7:30^1|notes}."]},
{sup:2, word:"flame", lines:["The flame of fire denotes the glory of God&rsquo;s holiness, which excluded fallen man from direct contact with God as the tree of life ({Gen3:24|Gen. 3:24} and {Gen3:17^1|note}). According to {Gen3:17|Gen. 3:17}-{Gen3:19|19} thorns were part of the curse that came because of man&rsquo;s sin. Hence, thorns are a symbol of fallen man under the curse. The thornbush here represents Moses himself as a redeemed sinner. The flame of fire burning within the thornbush signifies that the glory of God&rsquo;s holiness would burn within and upon Moses, God&rsquo;s called one, even though he was a sinner under God&rsquo;s curse. This was possible because of Christ&rsquo;s redemption ({Gen3:21|Gen. 3:21}; {Gen4:4|4:4}), which satisfied the requirements of God&rsquo;s holiness and removed the curse, allowing the divine fire (the Spirit) to visit and to indwell the thornbush (the redeemed sinner), making the fire one with the thornbush ({Gal3:13|Gal. 3:13}-{Gal3:14|14}). The fact that the fire burned in the thornbush without consuming it indicates that God Himself, not Moses, would be the &ldquo;fuel&rdquo; for the burning (cf. {Rom12:11|Rom. 12:11}; {2Ti1:7|2&nbsp;Tim. 1:7}; {Phi4:13|Phil. 4:13}; {Col1:29|Col. 1:29}). Moses would be only a vessel, a channel, through which the glory of God&rsquo;s holiness would be manifested (cf. {2Co4:7|2&nbsp;Cor. 4:7}). See {Exo3:11^1|note 11<sup>1</sup>}.","According to {Deu33:16|Deut. 33:16}, the thornbush was God&rsquo;s dwelling place. Since God&rsquo;s corporate people are His actual dwelling place ({Heb3:6|Heb. 3:6} and {Heb3:6^1|note}), this implies that the thornbush refers also to God&rsquo;s redeemed people as a corporate entity. After the tabernacle, a symbol of the children of Israel as God&rsquo;s dwelling place, was built up, at night the cloud of God&rsquo;s glory upon it had the appearance of fire ({Num9:15|Num. 9:15}-{Num9:16|16}). The fire burning upon the tabernacle signified that the people of Israel were a corporate burning thornbush. The church as God&rsquo;s dwelling place is also a burning thornbush&mdash;the Triune God burning within and upon a redeemed humanity ({Luk12:49|Luke 12:49}; {Act2:3|Acts 2:3}-{Act2:4|4}). Through the burning of the holy divine fire, the once cursed and redeemed thornbush is transformed to be God&rsquo;s dwelling place. This is God&rsquo;s economy."]},
{sup:"2c", word:"thornbush", vrefs:"Mark 12:26; Luke 20:37", lines:["See {Exo3:2^2|note 2<sup>2</sup>}."]},
],
