'4:3': [
{sup:1, word:"serpent", lines:["In {Exo3|chapter 3} God gave Moses the sign of the thornbush ({Exo3:2|3:2}-{Exo3:3|3}). In this chapter God gave Moses three additional signs as evidence that he had truly been called and sent by God. The meaning of the first sign, the sign of the staff becoming a serpent (vv. {Exo4:2|2}-{Exo4:4|4}), is that anything we rely on apart from God&mdash;our education, our occupation, etc.&mdash;is actually the hiding place of Satan, the usurping serpent. However, when at God&rsquo;s word we throw it down and then take it up again &ldquo;by the tail,&rdquo; i.e., in the way opposite to the practice of the worldly people, using it for God&rsquo;s purpose and not for ourselves, it becomes a staff of authority (vv. {Exo4:4|4}, {Exo4:17|17}; {Luk10:19|Luke 10:19}). In the second sign, the sign of the hand becoming leprous (vv. {Exo4:6|6}-{Exo4:7|7}), the bosom signifies what is within us, and leprosy signifies sin. This sign shows that our flesh is the embodiment of leprosy; in it there is nothing good, nothing but sin, corruption, and uncleanness ({Rom7:17|Rom. 7:17}-{Rom7:18|18}; cf. {Isa6:5|Isa. 6:5}). Nevertheless, when we obey the Lord by keeping His word, His cleansing power is able to make us clean (cf. {2Ki5:1|2&nbsp;Kings 5:1}-{2Ki5:14|14}). The meaning of the third sign, the sign of the water becoming blood ({Exo4:9|v. 9}), is that in the eyes of God all the earthly supply and worldly enjoyment (the water of the Nile) are nothing but death (blood). When they are poured out on that which produces life (the ground), immediately the death is exposed.","Satan is against Christ ({1Jo3:8|1&nbsp;John 3:8}); the flesh is against the Spirit ({Gal5:17|Gal. 5:17}); and the world is against the Father ({1Jo2:15|1&nbsp;John 2:15}). Hence, these three negative things are opposed to the Triune God and His economy. In one whom God has called, Satan, the flesh, and the world have lost their ground (cf. {Joh14:30|John 14:30}; {Gal5:24|Gal. 5:24}; {Gal6:14|6:14})."]},
],
