'13:17': [
{sup:1, word:"lead", lines:["God&rsquo;s people had God&rsquo;s command concerning the exodus from Egypt ({Exo12:21|12:21}-{Exo12:27|27}), but they needed the Lord&rsquo;s leading as well as His command. The Lord&rsquo;s leading is conditional. According to this chapter, in order to have God&rsquo;s leading, God&rsquo;s people need to be sanctified ({Exo13:2|v. 2}), to have a new beginning of a sinless life (vv. {Exo13:4|4}-{Exo13:7|7}), and to be in resurrection ({Exo13:19|v. 19})."]},
{sup:"a", word:"return", vrefs:"Num. 14:1-4; Neh. 9:17"},
],
'13:18': [
{sup:"1a", word:"around", vrefs:"cf. Num. 33:6-10", lines:["Because of the possibility of war with the Philistines, God did not lead the children of Israel in a straight way to the good land ({Exo13:17|v. 17}). Instead, He turned them around by the way of the wilderness to the Red Sea, leading them seemingly to a dead end ({Exo14:2|14:2}-{Exo14:3|3}). This tempted Pharaoh to pursue them and produced an ideal environment for God to baptize His people and bury Pharaoh and his army ({Exo14|ch. 14})."]},
],
'13:19': [
{sup:1, word:"bones", lines:["A bone signifies an unbreakable life, a life in resurrection ({Gen2:21|Gen. 2:21} and {Gen2:21^2|note 2}; {Joh19:33|John 19:33}, {Joh19:36|36}). Thus, the bringing of Joseph&rsquo;s bones out of Egypt into the good land signifies resurrection and indicates that those who share in the kingdom of God will no longer be in the natural life, signified by flesh and blood, but in the resurrection life, signified by Joseph&rsquo;s bones ({1Co15:50|1&nbsp;Cor. 15:50}). In the eyes of God all the children of Israel had been dead and buried in Egypt (see {Exo1:6^1|note 6<sup>1</sup>} in {Exo1|ch. 1}). The exodus from Egypt, therefore, was actually a resurrection. The exodus from the world, the genuine sanctification to the Lord ({Exo13:2|v. 2}), and a new beginning of a sinless life (vv. {Exo13:4|4}-{Exo13:7|7}) can be accomplished only by the resurrection life."]},
{sup:"a", word:"God", vrefs:"Gen. 50:25"},
{sup:"b", word:"bones", vrefs:"Josh. 24:32; Heb. 11:22"},
],
'13:20': [
{sup:"a", word:"Succoth", vrefs:"Exo. 12:37; Num. 33:6"},
],
'13:21': [
{sup:"1a", word:"cloud", vrefs:"Exo. 14:19-24; 40:38; Num. 9:15-23; 14:14; Deut. 1:33; Neh. 9:12, 19; Psa. 78:14; 99:7; 105:39; Isa. 4:5; 1&nbsp;Cor. 10:1; cf. Heb. 12:1", lines:["In typology the cloud signifies the Spirit ({1Co10:1|1&nbsp;Cor. 10:1}-{1Co10:2|2} and notes {1Co10:1^4|1<sup>4</sup>} and {1Co10:2^3|2<sup>3</sup>}), and the fire, for enlightening, signifies the Word of God ({Psa119:105|Psa. 119:105}). Hence, the instant, living leading from God comes through either the Spirit or the Word. The two pillars symbolize God Himself, for He is both the Spirit and the Word ({Joh4:24|John 4:24}; {Joh1:1|1:1}). Furthermore, the Word is also the Spirit ({Joh6:63|John 6:63}; {Eph6:17|Eph. 6:17}). Thus, God, the Word, and the Spirit are one to lead and guide us continually, whether by day or by night. In the Christian life there is no difference between day and night, for the light from the pillar of fire causes the night to become day."]},
],
