'19:10': [
{sup:"1a", word:"sanctify", vrefs:"Exo. 19:14; Lev. 20:7; Num. 11:18; Josh. 3:5; 7:13; 1&nbsp;Sam. 16:5; cf. Gen. 35:2", lines:["To be sanctified is to be separated from the world unto God (see {Joh17:17^1|note 17<sup>1</sup>} in {Joh17|John 17}). Through such a sanctification God&rsquo;s people can have fellowship with Him. See {Exo19:12^1|note 12<sup>1</sup>}."]},
],
'19:11': [
{sup:1, word:"third", lines:["The third day signifies resurrection ({1Co15:4|1&nbsp;Cor. 15:4}). God&rsquo;s people were brought into His presence in resurrection. To be in resurrection means that everything of the old creation, which is altogether natural, has been terminated, and the new creation, which is altogether in resurrection, is germinated ({2Co5:17|2&nbsp;Cor. 5:17})."]},
{sup:"a", word:"come", vrefs:"Exo. 34:5; Num. 11:25"},
{sup:2, word:"Mount", lines:["The mountain where the law was given has a twofold significance. First, as Mount Horeb, it is the mountain of God ({Exo3:1|3:1}, {Exo3:12|12}; {Exo4:27|4:27}; {Exo18:5|18:5}; {Exo24:13|24:13}; {Num10:33|Num. 10:33}; {1Ki19:8|1&nbsp;Kings 19:8}), the place for God&rsquo;s seekers to meet with one another ({Exo4:27|4:27}; {Exo18:5|18:5}), to meet with God ({Exo24:13|24:13}, {Exo24:15|15}-{Exo24:18|18}; {1Ki19:8|1&nbsp;Kings 19:8}), to serve God ({Exo3:12|3:12}), to receive God&rsquo;s revelation and vision ({Exo3:1|3:1}-{Exo3:3|3}; {Exo24:12|24:12}-{Exo24:13|13}; {1Ki19:8|1&nbsp;Kings 19:8}-{1Ki19:9|9}), and to be infused with God&rsquo;s substance ({Exo34:28|34:28}-{Exo34:29|29}). Second, as Mount Sinai (vv. {Exo19:11|11}, {Exo19:18|18}, {Exo19:20|20}-{Exo19:24|24}; {Exo34:2|34:2}-{Exo34:4|4}; {Gal4:24|Gal. 4:24}-{Gal4:25|25}), it is the place where the sinfulness of God&rsquo;s people is exposed and the boundary of God&rsquo;s holiness is revealed (vv. {Exo19:12|12}-{Exo19:13|13}, {Exo19:21|21}-{Exo19:24|24}; {Heb12:18|Heb. 12:18}-{Heb12:21|21})."]},
],
'19:12': [
{sup:1, word:"limits", lines:["In fellowship with God we know not only His grace ({Exo19:4|v. 4}) but also His holiness. Mount Sinai was a holy mountain because God descended upon it ({Exo19:20|v. 20}; cf. {Exo3:5|3:5}). Thus, a boundary was set which the children of Israel were not permitted to cross (vv. {Exo19:12|12}-{Exo19:13|13}, {Exo19:21|21}-{Exo19:24|24}). If we as God&rsquo;s people would remain in His presence in fellowship with Him, we must sanctify ourselves and everything related to us (vv. {Exo19:10|10}, {Exo19:14|14}, {Exo19:22|22}; cf. {Heb12:14|Heb. 12:14}). To be sanctified is to honor the boundary of God&rsquo;s holiness. Sanctification is the experiential aspect of holiness. When God&rsquo;s holiness becomes our experience, that is sanctification. See notes {Heb12:14^1|14<sup>1</sup>} in {Heb12|Heb. 12} and {Rom6:19^2|19<sup>2</sup>} in {Rom6|Rom. 6}."]},
{sup:"a", word:"mountain", vrefs:"Heb. 12:20"},
],
