'20:1': [
{sup:"a", word:"And", vrefs:"vv. 1-17: Deut. 5:4-21"},
{sup:1, word:"words", lines:["The law of God is God&rsquo;s word (in {Exo34:28|34:28} the Ten Commandments, the main contents of the law, are called &ldquo;the ten words&rdquo;&mdash;see {Exo34:28^1|note} there). As such, the law is God&rsquo;s testimony ({Exo16:34|16:34}; {Exo31:18|31:18}; {Exo32:15|32:15}; {Exo40:20|40:20}; {Psa19:7|Psa. 19:7}), God&rsquo;s expression, a revelation of God to His people (see notes {Joh1:1^2|1<sup>2</sup>} in {Joh1|John 1} and {Heb1:1^1P1|1<sup>1</sup>, par. 1}, in {Heb1|Heb. 1}). The law of God reveals God&rsquo;s attributes, showing that He is jealous (vv. {Exo20:4|4}-{Exo20:6|6}; cf. {2Co11:2|2&nbsp;Cor. 11:2}), holy (vv. {Exo20:7|7}-{Exo20:11|11}), loving (vv. {Exo20:6|6}, {Exo20:12|12}-{Exo20:15|15}; cf. {Rom13:8|Rom. 13:8}-{Rom13:10|10}; {Gal5:14|Gal. 5:14}), righteous ({Exo20:5|v. 5}), truthful ({Exo20:16|v. 16}; cf. {1Jo1:5|1&nbsp;John 1:5}-{1Jo1:6|6}), and pure (vv. {Exo20:2|2}-{Exo20:3|3}; {Exo20:17|17}). As the word of God and the testimony, the expression, of God, the law is a type of Christ as God&rsquo;s Word and God&rsquo;s testimony, God&rsquo;s expression ({Joh1:1|John 1:1}, {Joh1:18|18}; {Rev19:13|Rev. 19:13}; {Rev1:5|1:5}; {Col1:15|Col. 1:15}).","The reality of keeping the law is to live God and express God. Such a living, a living in the eternal economy of God, is the living of a God-man, a life of continually denying the self and being crucified to live Christ, who is God&rsquo;s testimony, by the bountiful supply of the Spirit of Jesus Christ for the enlarged and expanded expression of God ({Mat16:24|Matt. 16:24}; {Gal2:20|Gal. 2:20}; {Phi1:19|Phil. 1:19}-{Phi1:21|21a}; {Rom8:4|Rom. 8:4})."]},
],
'20:2': [
{sup:"1a", word:"Jehovah", vrefs:"Lev. 26:13; Psa. 81:10", lines:["The title Jehovah your God appears in the first five commandments (vv. {Exo20:2|2}-{Exo20:3|3}, {Exo20:4|4}-{Exo20:6|6}, {Exo20:7|7}, {Exo20:8|8}-{Exo20:11|11}, {Exo20:12|12}) but not in the last five (vv. {Exo20:13|13}-{Exo20:17|17}), indicating that the Ten Commandments are divided into two groups of five, the first group being related to God and the second group, to man (see {Exo20:12^1|note 12<sup>1</sup>})."]},
{sup:"b", word:"brought", vrefs:"Exo. 12:51"},
],
'20:3': [
{sup:"a", word:"other", vrefs:"2&nbsp;Kings 17:35; Isa. 45:21; Jer. 25:6; 35:15; Hosea 13:4"},
{sup:1, word:"before", lines:["Or, besides, in addition to. The first three commandments require man not to have any idols, any other beloved (see {Exo20:6^2|note 6<sup>2</sup>}), besides God ({Exo34:14|34:14}-{Exo34:17|17}; cf. {1Jo5:21^3P1|note 21<sup>3</sup>, par. 1}, in {1Jo5|1&nbsp;John 5} and notes {Jam4:4^1|4<sup>1</sup>} and {Jam4:5^1|5<sup>1</sup>} in {Jam4|James 4})."]},
],
